NFS
An nfs volume allows an existing NFS (Network File System) share to be mounted into a Pod. Unlike emptyDir,
which is erased when a Pod is removed, the contents of an nfs volume are preserved and the volume is merely unmounted.
This means that an NFS volume can be pre-populated with data, and that data can be shared between pods. NFS can be mounted by multiple writers simultaneously.
An NFS (Network File System) volume is a Kubernetes volume type that allows Pods to mount a directory from an external NFS server and use it as storage.

The NFS server is a separate machine (or VM) that exports a directory
Kubernetes Pods mount that directory over the network
The data lives outside the Pod and outside the node
volumes:
  - name: nfs-volume
    nfs:
      server: 10.0.0.50
      path: /nfs/shared-data
      Without NFS:

Each Pod has its own local storage
Data is duplicated
Hard to share state

With NFS:

One central storage location
All Pods read/write the same directory
Data persists even if Pods restart

CSI driver
A CSI driver (Container Storage Interface driver) is a standardized plugin that allows Kubernetes to connect with external storage systems 
(like cloud disks, network storage, or enterprise storage) in a consistent and portable way.
Before CSI, Kubernetes had in‑tree volume plugins:

Storage code was built inside Kubernetes
Adding or updating storage support required Kubernetes releases
Hard to maintain and extend

🔹 CSI solves this by moving storage logic outside Kubernetes.
A CSI driver is:

Software provided by a storage vendor
Runs outside the Kubernetes core
Implements the CSI specification
Allows Kubernetes to:

Create volumes
Attach/detach volumes
Mount/unmount volumes
Resize volumes
Take snapshots
>>Kubernetes talks to any storage system via its CSI driver.
Kubernetes needs storage
Kubernetes calls the CSI driver
CSI driver talks to the storage backend


